# Mession C++ Conventions

- Follow an Unreal-like style, but use this project's prefixes instead of Unreal's defaults.
- Prefix all structs with `S`, all classes with `M`, and all enums with `E`.
- Do not introduce new `F*`, `U*`, or `A*` type prefixes in new code. When refactoring touched code, prefer migrating names toward `S*`, `M*`, and `E*`.
- Keep boolean names in `bXxx` form. `InXxx` and `OutXxx` are allowed only for function parameters.
- Function, type, and enum names use PascalCase. Local variables and parameters use PascalCase unless an existing file clearly follows another established style.

# STL Wrapping Rule

- Do not use raw STL types directly in gameplay, server, networking, or shared domain code when introducing new dependencies on containers or utility types.
- Before using an STL facility, first expose it through a project-owned alias or wrapper in the core type layer, then use that project name everywhere else.
- Prefer extending the existing core type layer instead of scattering `std::vector`, `std::map`, `std::string`, `std::shared_ptr`, or similar types across feature code.
- If a required STL type does not yet have a project name, add the alias/wrapper first, then consume the project name in calling code.

# Safety Notes

- Keep packet parsing and serialization code explicit and bounds-checked.
- Avoid pointer-cast reads and writes such as `*(uint32*)&Buffer[0]`; prefer `memcpy` or typed serialization helpers.
